    "John Trapp": "And the city that is in the midst. ] See #Jos 13:9 .\nVer.\n16. I will not eat of thy bread. ] I need it not, as you mortal wights do, since Animantis cuiusque vita in fuga est, your life must be upheld by food, but not so mine: I am more than a creature. It is by degrees that Christ revealeth himself. And if thou wilt offer a burnt offering. ] Thou must be a willing offerer: God straineth upon no man. Virtus nolentium nulla est. Thou must offer it unto the Lord. ] And therefore to me, who am \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 , very God.\nVer.\n16. I will not eat of thy bread.] I need it not, as you mortal wights do, since Animantis cuiusque vita in fuga est, your life must be upheld by food, but not so mine: I am more than a creature. It is by degrees that Christ revealeth himself. And if thou wilt offer a burnt offering.] Thou must be a willing offerer: God straineth upon no man. Virtus nolentium nulla est. Thou must offer it unto the Lord.] And therefore to me, who am \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2, very God.\nVer.\n16. Abode in Gibeah of Benjamin. ] His own country, where he was likely to have the best assistance of his allies, but especially of Samuel\u2019s good company and prayers.\nVer.\n16. Abode in Gibeah of Benjamin.] His own country, where he was likely to have the best assistance of his allies, but especially of Samuel\u2019s good company and prayers.\nVer.",
    "Mark Allan Powell, Mark E. Biddle, Martin Luther": "; a possible allusion\nto the northern monarchy?).\u201d With the horns of a wild ox, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`\nwill drive out all his enemies, pushing them to the ends of the\nearth.\nZebulun and Issacar, 33:18-19\nZebulun and Issachar regularly appear together in tribal lists and in\nboth series of blessings. Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s blessing documents the commercial\nand geographical realities faced by these two tribes at home on\nIsrael\u2019s far northwestern frontier. Zebulun neighbored the trading\nand sea-faring Phoenicians whose principle trading centers were\nTyre and Sidon. The population of Issachar, apparently unable to\nsustain itself through agriculture or trade, had opted to make its\nliving as hired laborers. Not coincidentally, the etymology of\n[v_Gen_30_14] [v_Gen_30_15] [v_Gen_30_16] [v_Gen_30_17] [v_Gen_30_18] Issachar points to this choice (see Gen 30:14-18). Although Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u2019\nblessing may allude to these circumstances (\u201cin your going out\u201d\nand \u201cthey suck the riches of the sea\u201d probably refer to sea-going\n499\n[v_Deu_33_1] [v_Deu_33_2] [v_Deu_33_3] [v_Deu_33_4] [v_Deu_33_5] [v_Deu_33_6] [v_Deu_33_7] [v_Deu_33_8] [v_Deu_33_9] [v_Deu_33_10] [v_Deu_33_11] [v_Deu_33_12] [v_Deu_33_13] [v_Deu_33_14] [v_Deu_33_15] [v_Deu_33_16] [v_Deu_33_17] [v_Deu_33_18] [v_Deu_33_19] [v_Deu_33_20] [v_Deu_33_21] [v_Deu_33_22] [v_Deu_33_23] [v_Deu_33_24] [v_Deu_33_25] [v_Deu_33_26] [v_Deu_33_27] [v_Deu_33_28] [v_Deu_33_29] Deuteronomy 33:1-29\ncommerce, for example), it focuses on the sanctuary shared by\n[v_Hos_5_1] these two tribes, probably on Mt. Tabor `[place_Tabor_Jos_19]` (see Hos 5:1), where they\n\u201coffer right sacrifices\u201d ("
